{
  "doc_id": "4965",
  "text": "NK cells also express a wide range of cytokine receptors making them extremely responsive to cytokine stimulation. NK cells undergo dramatic shifts in phenotype and function in the presence of cytokines such as IL-2, IL-12, IL-15, and IL-18, singly and in combination [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . IL-2 plays a particularly critical role in activating NK cells by binding to the low affinity IL-2 receptor, a heterodimer of CD122 (IL-2Rβ) and CD132 (IL-2R , otherwise known as the common gamma chain). In general, NK cells do not express the high affinity IL-2 receptor, CD25 (IL-2R ). The CD56 bright NK cell subset expresses much higher levels of CD122 than the CD56 dim subset [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] ).",
